diary: I've been feeling pretty good! The twice daily runs and increased knee flexion seem to be working well.  My achilles problems are going away and very little anterior hip pain.  Also I've been doing a fair amount of inline skating, and perhaps that helps.  I recently started doing speed workouts with GVH again.  I've been doing doubles most days now, my secondary run no more than 1.5 miles for now (~15 minutes).  It's basically a warm-up.  I think this shakeout run has been very beneficial.  I've been staying home a lot and keeping myself somewhat isolated.  I rarely go to the office any more.    I have not updated my weight for a while.  Apparently I've lost some weight.

notes: I fell skating today and banged my left knee and hip.  The knee hurt a bit while running but otherwise the run was uneventful.

Tried running in shoes for this run.  A pair of Turntec Expanse TR shoes in my size have been sitting in the hall closet.  I think they were Daniel's.  Things I noticed:  * the knee flexion style of running I've been doing lately does not work.  * I found it impossible to not heel strike.  The knee flexion required to do that was too great.
Again with Allen, a little faster this time.  Felt good and relaxed.

I feel amazingly well after this ride and I'm grateful it worked out.  I met a girl named Coby who was really cool and we rode together for a while, starting at cardiac.  She passed me going up the hill.  She ahd a really nice butt.  She motivated me to push myself and keep up.  She disappeared after the race was over, presumably to avoid me.

right knee pain is subsiding but I have a nagging pain in the left posterior knee area.  It could be ITBS, a lower hamstring injury, or upper calf.  It's hard to tell now, but it hurts on resisted knee flexion.
diary: Did my first Century ride on Saturday 10/15/2011.  Foxy's Fall Century.  In the days since, I've noticed weight gain of about 5 lbs, apparently due to water retention.   I do not feel DOMS in any place in particular but my knees feel week.  My right knee has my classic injury, but it's getting better quickly.  Something is going on with my left knee too, but on the outside in back.  I've been going for short runs (1 mile) twice daily, but they are somewhat painful, especially the left knee.   I have not attempted to ride a bike except the day after the Century I peddled the bus-cycle around Davis with some others.

diary: Injured my right ankle today,  It was already hurting, and I stupidly went and did a bunch of hill repeats with GVH.   Pain is on the back of my heel, mostly on the lateral side but radiates to the the AT insertion.   Palpation of both medial and lateral sides of my heel is painful.   It's possibly a stress fracture of the calcaneous.  I'm not sure of this diagnosis but it seems to fit from the research I've done.  Another possibility, or in addition, there appears to be some damage to my peroneal tendon and/or the surrounding soft tissue structures.  I experience a clicking/popping on eversion & dorsiflexion and I can feel what I understand to be peroneal tendon subluxation.

I need to do something about that.

diary: I took a week off after what I think was a grade-2 calf strain in my medial gastroc, right side.  It came on as a sharp pain that made me stop immediately on my second run last tuesday, which was a routine short easy run.   The pain felt like contracted strands inside my muscle (radiating out to the sides and shin) on the verge of snapping.  It was very disquieting, and I had to stop and sit down a few times in order to let the calf relax.  It struck a few more times as I walked home.  Some things to note: I had recently started doing static stretches, and I had been experiencing a dull soleus/AT pain.  I had been doing a lot of hill springing.  I think I might have gotten carried away with that.  I had recently had a conflict with Tim about an email I sent to the Landlord, which was a little snarky towards Tim.  I had been angry about Tim's lack of consideration.  A week later (today) I walked 8 miles with a few short jogs.  No calf pain. I hope to keep things that way.  I started walking twice daily as soon as I could put weight on it.  I kept it to a short loop at first so I could get home immediately if it started to hurt, and it did for the first couple of days.

diary: I'm taking it easy because I hurt my left AT last week and it's not getting better.  Time to go back to basics: two 20 minute walks per day, build back up the mileage.  I let the miles slip and found myself doing a few 8 mile runs per week and nothing else.  I need to get back to every day running, even if most of the runs are short.   Both ATs hurt now.  The right-ouer AT has been an ongoing issue for a couple months now, and my left inner AT might actually be a FHL issue, as my left hallux is notoriously stiff.  Left hip flexor/adductor is tight and prevents the extension I want.  I believe this is happening in conjunction with my left ankle issue.

Left getting better, ankle not getting worse :p

The higher running volume has been bringing back some AT troubles, although fairly manageable.  In particular, after yesterday's mile repeats my left AT is noticeable when walking.  I really need to watch it.
My second day of complete rest.  I'm going nuts.  In an attempt to fix my Iliopsoas problem I have not done any running or elliptical, and even minimized my cycling and walking.

Saw a chiropractor today, Dr. Hartz.   He was not able to find anything worth correcting except a slight rotation in my hip, which he says probably won't affect my current hip flexor injury and that probably I just need to rest more.  Walking has been going well.  I'm going for 10 hours of walking this week.  Hip flexor is getting better.  I've been doing some resisted hip flexion exercises, some with a bicycle tube, focusing on flexion past 90 degrees.
I'm intentionally taking this whole week off from all endurance activities.  Long skates were starting to hurt my right AT at insertion.
I'm sick with a head cold.  Taking a day off today.  I feel tired but no injuries.
I injured my right soleus/AT at yesterday's 3K time trial. It had been tight for a few weeks but now it's an injury.  I cannot run.  I think this is going to be a while.  Damn it!!
I'm attempting abstinence from masturbation, starting today.  I'm not sure how long I'll try to sustain it.  I'm curious to see how it affects me.
I did some extensive cross-friction work on my calves today.  It was quite painful.

I have definitely re-injured my right AT. It hurts to walk today. Hopefully a few days off will take care of it.  I have been high for most of my runs and I'm basically high all the time.  Perhaps ""medicated"" is a better description.  I have been focusing on natural surfaces.  I run trails as much as possible and I've been exploring out Notrth-east of Davis a bit.

I have been rolling out my back a lot lately.  Michae believes a lot of problems originate at the spine.  I've noticed more trouble spots on the left side of my spine, and in general on the left side of my body all the way down.
My right arch is injured, under the 1st metatarsal (controlling the big toe).  This may be the same injury from Malibu half marathon 2009.

It turns out the arch pain was a reaction to a bee sting.  I was in a lot of pain for two days and today it's mostly gone.  The interesting thing is that it was itching, so I examined more carefully and found the bee stinger.  I guess the swelling compressed my plantar fascia and caused what felt like  fascial strain.
hurt my left AT (tarsal tunnel syndrome) and cannot walk.
